04560nam a22006735i 9780271022727DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212006pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710227277 a10.1515/97802710227272doi  a(DE-B1597)584019  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDC36.9b.D49 2006 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a944.00722221 aDewald, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLost Worlds :bThe Emergence of French Social History, 1815-1970 /cJonathan Dewald. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Historians and Modernity -- t1 "À la Table de Magny": Men of Letters and Historical Writing in Nineteenth-Century Paris -- t2 Ordering Time: The Problem of French Chronology -- t3 God and the Historian: Sainte-Beuve's Port-Royal -- t4 Lost Worlds: Lucien Febvre and the Alien Past -- t5 Private Lives and Historical Knowledge -- t6 Nobles as Signifiers: Making Sense of a Class Structure -- t7 An Alternative Path to Rural History -- tConclusion: On the Politics of Social History -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday's interest in social history and private life is often seen as a twentieth-century innovation. Most often Lucien Febvre and the Annales school in France are credited with making social history a widely accepted way for historians to approach the past. In Lost Worlds historian Jonathan Dewald shows that we need to look back further in time, into the nineteenth century, when numerous French intellectuals developed many of the key concepts that historians employ today.According to Dewald, we need to view Febvre and other Annales historians as participants in an ongoing cultural debate over the shape and meanings of French history, rather than as inventors of new topics of study. He closely examines the work of Charles-Augustin Sainte-Beuve, Hippolyte Taine, the antiquarian Alfred Franklin, Febvre himself, the twentieth-century historian Philippe Ariès, and several others. A final chapter compares specifically French approaches to social history with those of German historians between 1930 and 1970. Through such close readings Dewald looks beyond programmatic statements of historians' intentions to reveal how history was actually practiced during these years.A bold work of intellectual history, Lost Worlds sheds much-needed light on how contemporary ideas about the historian's task came into being. Understanding this larger context enables us to appreciate the ideological functions performed by historical writing through the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aHistoriographyzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aHistoriographyzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial historyy19th century. 0aSocial historyy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271022727zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271022727423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271022727/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK